         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
<ab><lb n="1"/><w lemma="αὔξι">αὔξι</w> <persName type="divine" ref="#aphrodite"><!-- think --><addName nymRef="#Οὐρανία">Οὐρανία</addName> <w lemma="ὁ">ἡ</w> <addName nymRef="μέγας">μεγάλη</addName></persName>  
   <lb n="2"/><w lemma="τύχη"><unclear>τύ</unclear>χη</w>    <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <w lemma="δοῦλος">δούλου</w> <w lemma="σύ">ϲου</w>
   <lb n="3"/><w lemma="αὔξι">αὔξι</w> <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w> <persName type="attested" ref="http://www.lgpn.ox.ac.uk/id/V5b-13673"><name nymRef="#Χρυσόμαλλος">Χρ<unclear>υ</unclear>σόμαλλοϲ</name></persName>
   <lb n="4"/><w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w> <w lemma="πήγνυμι"><unclear>π</unclear>ήξαϲ</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τὸ</w> <w lemma="μάρμαρος">μάρμαρον</w></ab>
</div>
         <div type="apparatus">
           <listApp>
            <app loc="2"><note>Perhaps εὐχή</note></app>
              <app loc="4"><rdg resp="#cpj2013">τήξας</rdg><note>The Π is roughly cut, Jones suggested a reference to a performer 
               who 'has melted the marble' by his powerful performance; Roueché reads the second upright as a deliberate line, rather than a casual scratch.
</note></app>
           </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#roueche1993">
            <p>Power to Ourania the great, fortune of your servant! Power to Chrysomallos, who fixed the marble!</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr2008b">
            <p>Strength to Ourania the mighty, fortune of your servant! <note>or</note> Strength to Ourania, the mighty fortune of your servant! Strength to Chrysomallos, who fixed the marble!</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#cpj2013">
            <p>Power to Ourania the great fortune of your servant! Power to Chrysomallos, he who melted the marble!</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
           <!-- ADD check<p>, add see SEG 63_856-oueché, Performers 42/43 no. 12 (SEG LVIII 1163; I.Aphr. 2.2). C.P.Jones, EA 46 (2013) 169-171, argues that in lines 1-2 (αὔξι Οὐρανία ἡ μεγάλη | τύχη τοῦ δούλου σου) 
               it is Aphrodite’s favor which ‘had brought to Χρυσόμαλλος [L. 4; a pantomime] “good fortune” in competition with rivals’ (170) and in L. 4 ὁ τήξας τὸ μάρμαρον should be read:
               ‘he who melted the marble’ (Roueché read πήξας and translated ‘fixed the marble’). The pantomime’s performance was so phenomenal that ‘it “melted” even the marble of the building’.</p>
        --> </div>
